questions.query: What specific problems or challenges in the Ethereum ecosystem does your project address? How does your solution improve upon existing alternatives?
questions.explanation: Currently accessing dWebsites (Decentralized Websites)  is not an easy task for the average user. The content can be stored on various storage protocols such as IPFS, Arweave and Swarm. The average user is not running multiple nodes and able to access this content. eth.limo acts as a bridge to web3 enabling the average user to access decentralized content from any browser without special software or technical knowledge.

questions.query: Outline your project's roadmap and how the grant funds will be used to achieve your development goals.
questions.explanation:
Here's a link to some recent achievements and our some of our future roadmap plans. https://discuss.ens.domains/t/eth-limo-update/19707

Publish some interesting WASM tools we’ve been developing internally to allow self-hosted serverless functions for ENS domains.

Continue improvements of eth.limo and eth.link

Release an MVP of our in-browser, resolution service worker app that performs trustless IPFS content verification.

questions.query: How does your project contribute to the decentralization and security of the Ethereum network?
questions.explanation:
LIMO takes public gateway services a step further by enforcing strong privacy guarantees such as
never logging IP addresses or engaging in TCP fingerprinting. Limo now actively blocks FLoC
(Federated Learning of Cohorts). This is a Google developed algorithm that tracks and correlates users
based on their browsing history. FLoC enables advanced fingerprinting capabilities and greatly
undermines online privacy and anonymity.

questions.query: How does your project contribute significantly to the Ethereum network's infrastructure? Please provide specific examples and metrics if available.
questions.explanation: ETH.LIMO is a free and public ENS gateway that enables users to access Ethereum-native dApps and content. The eth.limo gateway is the default resolver for app.ens.domains and numerous other ENS projects.  On average the eth.limo gateway handles over 1B requests per year. https://docs.google.com/document/d/10h7SEwr1ANJFwzWDsdfWc67nFjprMafWZZVKkUGrf0Q/edit?tab=t.0  - some previous metrics

questions.query: Describe any pioneering development work in your project, particularly in enhancing privacy, interoperability, or user experience.
questions.explanation: eth.limo  is a privacy-preserving ENS gateway that does not log IP addresses or any identifiable information that could single out a unique user. We’ve dedicated efforts to enhance the performance and reliability of our service, incorporating new features based on valuable feedback from the community.

questions.query: What specific problems or challenges in the Ethereum ecosystem does your project address? How does your solution improve upon existing alternatives?
questions.explanation: There is a substantial need for accessibility for projects and users seeking to utilize ENS dWebsites. Research has indicated that ENS dWebsite traffic is growing at a rapid pace. On average the eth.limo gateway handles 4-7M+ requests per day. At present, the primary source of raw traffic for eth.limo is derived from DAOs, DeFi apps and their related products/services, SEO crawlers, and novel projects within the community. On the long tail, eth.limo serves a diverse range of independent dWebsites, spanning from personal resumes and portfolios, to custom NFT art projects.

questions.query: Outline your project's roadmap and how the grant funds will be used to achieve your development goals.
questions.explanation:
1. Existing operational capabilities and associated costs (eth.limo/eth.link/gno.limo).
2. Personnel and consultants (including on-call support).
3. Infrastructure scaling/new deployments.
4. Unforeseen and unexpected costs from “known-unknowns”.
5. Continued integrations and broader contentHash codec handling.
6. Responding to and mitigating abusive content.
7. Providing support for both end users and developers.
8. Continued performance and resiliency optimizations.
9. Continued development and operational work on “trustless”, client-side ENS and IPFS content verification service workers.
10. Ad-hoc development based on user/community requests and feedback (new integrations, tools, services, etc…).

questions.query: How does your project contribute to the decentralization and security of the Ethereum network?
questions.explanation: eth.limo resolves ENS dWebsites natively in the browser which provides projects and users an alternative means of resolving front-ends/user generated content from the Ethereum blockchain.Also as a result of assuming operational responsibility for the eth.link service, we have also become the default ENS resolver for IPFS Shipyard developed tools such as Kubo and Rainbow as well as for the dweb.link and ipfs.io gateway services. In addition to dns.eth.link, we also support all traffic originating from resolver.cloudflare-eth.com as a result of service deprecation.
